<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Drip for Strawberries</span>
            <h2>The Case for Drip in Berry Production</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon"><i data-lucide="heart"></i></div>
                <h3>Botrytis Elimination</h3>
                <p>Botrytis gray mold needs free moisture on foliage and fruit to infect. Drip irrigation never wets the canopy — eliminating the primary infection pathway without additional fungicide applications.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon"><i data-lucide="leaf"></i></div>
                <h3>Powdery Mildew Control</h3>
                <p>While powdery mildew thrives in humid conditions, keeping leaf surfaces dry through drip irrigation significantly reduces spore establishment and colony development throughout the season.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon"><i data-lucide="flask-conical"></i></div>
                <h3>Calcium Fertigation</h3>
                <p>Tip burn and hollow core are calcium mobility issues. Drip fertigation delivers calcium directly to the root zone where it's available for rapid uptake — replacing the less reliable foliar calcium programs.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon"><i data-lucide="ruler"></i></div>
                <h3>Consistent Fruit Size</h3>
                <p>Inconsistent soil moisture during fruit development causes bimodal size distributions that hurt packout percentages. Drip's precise moisture control maintains a narrow matric potential range that drives uniform fruit sizing.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon"><i data-lucide="thermometer"></i></div>
                <h3>Frost Protection Compatible</h3>
                <p>Many strawberry SDI systems are designed to deliver water during frost events via overhead compensation — or simply provide the soil heat reservoir that reduces the temperature drop during radiation frost nights.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight-card">
                <div class="highlight-card-icon"><i data-lucide="bar-chart-2"></i></div>
                <h3>Case Study: Oxnard, CA</h3>
                <p>A 480-acre berry operation switched from overhead sprinklers to drip and saw Botrytis field presence drop from 22% to 8% of fruit, Class 1 packout improve from 71% to 86%, and water use drop by 54%.</p>
                <a href="/growers-stories" class="btn-primary-sm" style="margin-top:16px;">Read More →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

